50|$|Specific {{prisoner}} transport restraints (e.g. Smith & Wesson model 1850 transport restraint) are combinations which {{consist of}} a pair of handcuffs, attached by a longer chain to a pair of <b>leg</b> <b>irons.</b> When being placed in such transport restraints, the prisoner will still have the possibility to manage normal steps, but is prevented from running by the <b>leg</b> <b>irons.</b> The connecting chain also prevents the prisoner from lifting his arms. For transporting prisoners by car, special combinations called auto restraint are used where the chains of the <b>leg</b> <b>irons</b> as well as the connecting chains are shortened, allowing the prisoner only a stooping shuffling walk when he is outside the car.|$|R
50|$|Two ankle {{shackles}} {{attached to}} each other by a short length of chain are known as a hobble or as <b>leg</b> <b>irons.</b> These could be chained to a much longer chain with several other prisoners, creating a work crew known as a chain gang. The walk required to avoid tripping while in <b>leg</b> <b>irons</b> {{is known as the}} convict shuffle.|$|R
5000|$|Tubac Jail: Wooden post in {{the ground}} with an {{attached}} pair of <b>leg</b> <b>irons</b> to hold the prisoner. The <b>leg</b> <b>irons</b> were originally used on board a Spanish ship to chain prisoners to the mast before being used as the town jail in Tubac, Arizona. They are now {{on display in the}} museum of the Tubac Presidio State Historic Park.|$|R
